\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Roy rappaport - religion. Argues that all religion consists of three components. First are the ultimate sacred propositions, beliefs considered irrefutable despite the fact that there is no empirical evidence to support them. These propositions direct the second component, ritual, which must be performed repeatedly and correctly in order to achieve its goals. If done correctly, ritual induces the third component, an awe-inspiring experience.  Because this experience deeply stirs the emotions, it verifies teh sacred propositions in a way that cold, hard logic never could. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ritual is the key component of this self-validating system.  Paraphernalia, costume, pigments, and musical instruments, performed over and over again.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Chimps - dominance hierarchy.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Chimps cannot do what human foragers do: accumulate social obligations with their neighbors as a hedge against lean times.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The headmen of foraging groups were not bullies. They were generous modest and diplomatic, because their constituents were too skilled at alliance building to put up with bullies. The fat e of the bully was to lure them into a bush and pincushion them with arrows.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 KEY: early humans considered themselves as part of a natural/supernatural dominance hierarchy, where humans could be nothing more than a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91gamma\u8217\'92. Celestial alphas were the source of the ultimate sacred proposition. Ancestors were beta, and the focus of ritual. Emotions of living gammas was where the awe happens. }
